The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Saturday, November 05, 2005 

 Bangalore season from today 

 WILLIAM TELL

 Bangalore: The 36-day Bangalore winter season 2005-06, which starts on Saturday, will conclude on March 31. The season will see approximately 800 horses vying for stakes of approximately Rs 9.6 crore ? an increase of 10 per cent compared to the last winter season.

 Eighty jockeys, including two from abroad, and 37 A licensed trainers are expected take part during the season.

 The highlight of the season will be the Invitation Cup weekend on March 4 and 5. Racing, otherwise, will be held on Fridays and Saturdays. 

 Concurrently the Mysore winter racing will be held for 15 Days, mainly on Wednesday. A maximum of 8 races will be conducted on all race days excepting the classic days when the number of events may go up.

 The following races will be sponsored events: 

 The Harvins Bangalore 2000 Guineas, the Kelachandra New Millennium Cup, the Karnataka Racehorse Owners Association Trophy and the Poonawalla Bangalore Winter Derby which will have Rs 16 lakhs as added money.

 Trainers D. Byramji and S. Ganapathy have the pick of the two-year-old youngsters in their yards and they may strike early.

 The following are the important meetings: Bangalore 1000 Guineas (on November 26), the Bangalore Turf Club Trophy (December 3), The Harvins Bangalore 2000 Guineas (Dec10), the Bangalore Oaks (January 6), the Chief Ministers Trophy (Jan 13), the Poonawalla Derby (Jan 26), the Bangalore Winter Million (Feb 18), the Governors Trophy (Feb 25), the Sprinters amp; Stayers Cup (March 4), the Indian Turf Invitation Cup (March 5) and the Bangalore Juvenile Million (March 31).There are eight events in Saturdays race card featuring the 1,200m Rajyotsava Trophy which may see Darius Byramji-ward Supreme Power winning it from Corsican Gal. The The Razeen-Divine Colours gelding had finished a close fourth to Splash Of Class in his last outing. when he came from way behind.

 Supreme Power may, however, face some challenge from in-form speedsters Time To Celebrate, Corsican Gal and Show In Tell. But being in good nick and also going by his blazing trials, C. Alford may drive the Power home to victory.

 There are 10 juveniles making their debut in the 1,100m Inauguration Plate but Ganapathys Peace Prize and Jaggy Dhariwals Secret Wish appear to be in forward condition than the rest in the field. Between the two, the former ? a Burden Of Proof-Sabre Dance filly, may just about have the measure of her half-sister who is out of Secret Wish.

